  "prompt": "How do I Integrate: 1/ (1- x^3)?",
  "response": "To integrate 1/(1-x\u00b3), we'll use partial fraction decomposition and logarithmic integration. Here's a step-by-step solution:\n\n1) The integral is \u222b 1/(1-x\u00b3) dx\n\n2) This can be decomposed as:\n   1/(1-x\u00b3) = (A/1) + (Bx + C)/(1-x\u00b3)\n\n3) Finding the coefficients:\n   1 = A(1-x\u00b3) + (Bx + C)\n   1 = A - Ax\u00b3 + Bx + C\n\n4) Comparing coefficients gives:\n   A = 1\n   B = 0\n   C = 0\n\n5) So, \u222b 1/(1-x\u00b3) dx = \u222b (1/(1-x\u00b3)) dx\n\n6) This can be integrated using the substitution:\n   u = 1-x\u00b3\n   du = -3x\u00b2 dx\n   dx = -du/(3x\u00b2)\n\n7) The integral becomes:\n   -(1/3) \u222b (1/u) du\n\n8) This results in:\n   -(1/3) ln|u| + C\n\n9) Substituting back:\n   -(1/3) ln|1-x\u00b3| + C\n\nThis is the final solution to the integral.",
